		<hr />
		
		
			<div><strong>Best way to sustain DPS on raid encounters</strong><br />&nbsp;</div>
		
		
		
		<div>I know it's possible to generate huge DPS on the short-term.  On new spells, there isn't anything really efficient short of &quot;chain-casting&quot; Claw of Selay.  The instant nukes are nice for their quick casts and -50 resist mods, but they really hog mana big-time.  The conventional nukes are, at first glance, more mana-efficient, but the lack of a decent resist mod makes them get resisted way more often which basically cancels the efficiency.<br />
<br />
Thus, I am finding myself running out of mana 3 to 4 minutes (just guessing there) into a fight even after using harvest, but I have been mixing in cloudburst strikes as well.  Is going with the magic line (for lower focus penalties) making a difference for those of you who are trying that?  I may have to spend 30 AA to get that flappy.<br />
<br />
The only parallel to the old tactic of casting Chaos Flame until GOM procs is casting Claw (which is sooooo slow) and then either Cold Snap (which can slow your claws even more) or whatever the conventional ice nuke is when GORM procs.  Not the huge DPS we dreamed of. . .<br />
<br />
Another thing I considered is casting Claw (I have rank II whoopie) and then EC when GORM procs, but this would require me to lose flappy focus on one or the other (no bard song for level 71+ and I don't get grouped with bards that often).  I have tried using concussive blast to determine nukes to use (by the proc) but that mixes foci again.  <br />
<br />
I have a 13k mana pool or so raid buffed.   Just curious what the rest of you are doing.  I know I should probably re-roll my wizard for asking this (j/k, Kela!) but I am getting frustrated with being oom so fast and THEN having to chain cast Claw of Selay.  I want to be the best wizard I can be but no point in walking the aggro line early when I am just gonna be oom.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br /><table class="tborder" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="1" border="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td class="page">
	
		<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
		<tr valign="bottom">
			<td style="font-size:14pt">Kela</td>
			<td class="smallfont" align="right">October 31st, 2006 04:45 PM</td>
		</tr>
		</table>
		
		<hr />
		
		
		
		
		<div>Actually I welcome questions and encourage wizards that wish to make themselves better.  Give me an average wizard who wants to learn over one who refuses to play any day of the week.   Anyways....<br />
<br />
I glanced at your gear and since you said you have 13k mana I assume the magelo is a bit out of date.  You're really hurting yourself without magic focus at this point in time in my opinion.  Right now the absolute best ANY wizard can do, and this includes the one or two wizards that have located new fire focuses, is with the magic line of spells.  There are simply too many focuses that are being degraded too heavily to use any other spells.  The cold spells are 74/73 I believe, Fire 74/75 and magic are 73/72.  <br />
<br />
Now I speak from someone who has focuses that go up to level 72.  Even if your focuses only apply up to 70, its still obviously better to go with the lowest possible level spell.  Every single raid that I've encountered during this expansion, Ball Lightning and Cloudburst Strike have maximized my DPS.  I cast Patient Harvest at around 65% mana so that it will come back up sooner.  I also click any mod rod I might have long before I really need it so that it will also refresh sooner.  <br />
<br />
I've never been one to use Claw of Vox in the past so I've kept Claw of Selay tucked away.  I've always found its better to use regular nukes unless we're talking a 30 minute steady fight which I have yet to see.  <br />
<br />
I really think the biggest problem people are ignoring are their focuses.  Ball Lightning is more efficient of a spell than Sothgar's Flame (last I checked it was, that might have been pre release)  Some people might claim how wonderful rains are but I rarely find them appropriate and can't speak from personal experience with those..I believe tears is level 71 so that would be acceptable to use although there aren't any other good fire spells to use at that level.  A magic rain would ahve been nice.<br />
<br />
Ball and Cloud....only way to fly.  I'd also never use Cold Snap unless I was soloing or exclusively casting instants.  But like Gem said...I micromanage my DPS to the last 0.0001.  And I've never met a wizard who could consistantly outparse me.</div>
	</td>
</tr>
